<h1>Area of Trapezoid</h1>
<p>The <strong>area of a trapezoid</strong> is the number of unit squares t=
hat can be fit into it and it is measured in square units (like cm<sup>2</s=
up>, m<sup>2</sup>, in<sup>2</sup>, etc). For example, if 15 unit squares e=
ach of length 1 cm can be fit inside a trapezoid, then its area is 15 cm<su=
p>2</sup>. A trapezoid is a type of quadrilateral with one pair of parallel=
 sides (which are known as bases). It means the other pair of sides can be =
non-parallel (which are known as legs). It is not always possible to draw u=
nit squares and measure the area of a trapezoid. So, let us learn about the=
 trapezoid area formula and learn how to find the area of a trapezoid witho=
ut the height in this article.</p>
