<div id=3D"What-is-the-Area-of-Trapezoid">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>What is the Area of Trapezoid?</h2>
</div>
<p>The area of a trapezoid is the total space covered by its sides. An inte=
resting point to be noted here is that if we know the length of all the sid=
es we can simply split the trapezoid into smaller <a href=3D"https://www.cu=
emath.com/geometry/polygons/">polygons</a> like triangles and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://www.cuemath.com/geometry/rectangle/">rectangles</a>, find their area,=
 and add them up to get the area of the trapezoid. However, there is a dire=
ct formula that is used to find the area of a trapezoid if we know certain =
dimensions.</p>
<div id=3D"Area-of-Trapezoid-Formula">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Area of Trapezoid Formula</h2>
</div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/measurement/area/">area</a> of a =
<a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/geometry/trapezoid/">trapezoid</a> can b=
e calculated if the length of its parallel sides and the distance (height) =
between them is given. The formula for the area of a trapezoid is expressed=
 as,</p>
<p><strong>A =3D =C2=BD (a + b) h</strong></p>
<p>where<strong> </strong> (A) is the area of a trapezoid, 'a' and 'b' are =
the bases (parallel sides), and 'h' is the height (the <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.cuemath.com/geometry/perpendicular/">perpendicular</a> distance between =
a and b)</p>
<p><strong><img alt=3D"Area of trapezoid formula" src=3D"https://d138zd1ktt=
9iqe.cloudfront.net/media/seo_landing_files/area-of-trapezoid-1644815290.pn=
g" style=3D"width: 400px;"></strong></p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<p>Find the area of a trapezoid whose parallel sides are 32 cm and 12 cm, r=
espectively, and whose height is 5 cm.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The bases are given as, a =3D 32 cm; b =3D 12 cm; the height is h =3D 5 =
cm.</p>
<p>The area of the trapezoid =3D A =3D =C2=BD (a + b) h</p>
<p>A =3D =C2=BD (32 + 12) =C3=97 (5) =3D =C2=BD (44) =C3=97 (5) =3D 110 cm<=
sup>2</sup>.</p>
<div id=3D"Area-of-Trapezoid-without-Height">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Area of Trapezoid without Height</h2>
</div>
<p>When all the sides of the trapezoid are known, and we do not know the he=
ight we can find the area of the trapezoid. In this case, we first need to =
calculate the height of the trapezoid. Let us understand this with the help=
 of an example. It is to be noted that this method can be used in the case =
of an isosceles trapezoid.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Find the area of a trapezoid in which the base=
s (parallel sides) are given as 6 and 14 units respectively, and the non-pa=
rallel sides (legs) are given as, 5 units each.</p>
<p><img alt=3D"area of trapezoid without height" src=3D"https://d138zd1ktt9=
iqe.cloudfront.net/media/seo_landing_files/trapezoid-1683114910.png" style=
=3D"width: 450px;"></p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Let us calculate the area of the trapezoid us=
ing the following steps.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Step 1:</strong> We know that the area of a trapezoid =3D =C2=
=BD (a + b) h; where h =3D height of the trapezoid which is not given in th=
is case; a =3D 6 units, b =3D 14 units, non parallel sides (legs) =3D 5 uni=
ts each. This means that it is an isosceles trapezoid because the non-paral=
lel sides are equal in length.</li>
<li><strong>Step 2:</strong> So, if we find the height of the trapezoid, we=
 can calculate the area. If we draw the height of the trapezoid on both sid=
es we can see that the trapezoid is split into a rectangle ABQP and 2 <a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/geometry/right-angled-triangle/">right-angled=
 triangles</a>, ADP and BQC.</li>
<li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Since a rectangle has equal opposite sides, th=
is means AP =3D BQ and it is given that the sides AD =3D BC =3D 5 units. So=
, the height AP and BQ can be calculated using the <a href=3D"https://www.c=
uemath.com/geometry/pythagoras-theorem/">Pythagoras theorem.</a></li>
<li><strong>Step 4:</strong> Now, let us find the length of DP and QC. Sinc=
e ABQP is a rectangle, AB =3D PQ and DC =3D 14 units. This means PQ =3D 6 u=
nits, and the remaining combined length of DP + QC can be calculated as fol=
lows. DC - PQ =3D 14 - 6 =3D 8. So, 8 =C3=B7 2 =3D 4 units. Therefore, DP =
=3D QC =3D 4 units.</li>
<li><strong>Step 5:</strong> Now, the height of the trapezoid can be calcul=
ated using the Pythagoras theorem. Taking the right-angled triangle ADP, we=
 know that AD =3D 5 units, DP =3D 4 units, so AP =3D =E2=88=9A(AD<sup>2</su=
p> - DP<sup>2</sup>) =3D =E2=88=9A(5<sup>2</sup> - 4<sup>2</sup>) =3D =E2=
=88=9A(25 - 16) =3D =E2=88=9A9 =3D 3 units. Since ABQP is a rectangle, in w=
hich the opposite sides are equal, AP =3D BQ =3D 3 units.</li>
<li><strong>Step 6:</strong> Now, that we know all the dimensions of the tr=
apezoid including the height, we can calculate its area using the formula, =
area of a trapezoid =3D =C2=BD (a + b) h; where h =3D 3 units, a =3D 6 unit=
s, b =3D 14 units. After substituting the values in the formula, we get, ar=
ea of a trapezoid =3D =C2=BD (a + b) h =3D =C2=BD (6 + 14) =C3=97 3 =3D =C2=
=BD =C3=97 20 =C3=97 3 =3D 30 unit<sup>2</sup>.</li>
</ul>
<div id=3D"how-to-derive-area-of-trapezoid-formula">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>How to Derive Area of Trapezoid Formula?</h2>
</div>
<p>We can prove the area of a trapezoid formula by using a <a href=3D"https=
://www.cuemath.com/geometry/triangles/">triangle</a> here. Taking a trapezo=
id of bases 'a' and 'b' and height 'h', let us prove the formula.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Step 1:</strong> Split one of the legs into two equal parts and=
 cut a triangular portion of the trapezoid as shown below.</li>
<li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Attach it at the bottom as shown, such that it=
 forms a big triangle.</li>
</ul>
<p><img alt=3D"Proof of area of trapezoid formula" src=3D"https://d138zd1kt=
t9iqe.cloudfront.net/media/seo_landing_files/how-to-derive-or-prove-area-of=
-trapezoid-formula-1613475295.png" style=3D"width: 450px;"></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Step 4:</strong> This way, the trapezoid is rearranged as a tri=
angle. Even after we attach it this way, we know that the area of the trape=
zoid and the new big triangle remains the same. We can also see that the ba=
se of the new big triangle is (a + b) and the height of the triangle is h.<=
/li>
<li><strong>Step 5:</strong> So, it can be said that the area of the trapez=
oid =3D the <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/measurement/area-of-triangle=
/">area of the triangle</a></li>
<li><strong>Step 6:</strong> This can be written as,<strong> </strong>area =
of the trapezoid =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 base =C3=97 height =3D =C2=BD (a + b) h<=
/li>
</ul>
<p>Thus, we have proved the formula for finding the area of a trapezoid.</p=
