<li class=3D"cue-slide" id=3D"slide-188">
<div>
<p><strong>Example 1:</strong> If one of the bases of a trapezoid is equal =
to 8 units, its height is 12 units and its area is 108 square units, find t=
he length of the other base.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>One of the bases is 'a' =3D 8 units.</p>
<p>Let the other base be 'b'.</p>
<p>The area of the trapezoid is, A =3D 108 square units.</p>
<p>Its height is 'h' =3D 12 units.</p>
<p>Substitute all these values in the area of trapezoid formula,</p>
<p>A =3D =C2=BD (a + b) h</p>
<p>108 =3D =C2=BD (8 + b) =C3=97 (12)</p>
<p>108 =3D 6 (8 + b)</p>
<p>Dividing both sides by 6,</p>
<p>18 =3D 8 + b</p>
<p>b =3D 10</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> The length of the other base of the given trape=
zoid =3D 10 units.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li class=3D"cue-slide" id=3D"slide-42">
<div>
<p><strong>Example 2:</strong> Find the area of an isosceles trapezoid in w=
hich the length of each leg is 8 units and the bases are equal to 13 units =
and 17 units respectively.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The bases are a =3D 13 units and b =3D 17 units. Let us assume that its =
height is h.</p>
<p>We can divide the given trapezoid into two congruent right triangles and=
 a rectangle as follows:</p>
<p><img alt=3D"area of trapezoid with sides and without height example prob=
lem" src=3D"https://d138zd1ktt9iqe.cloudfront.net/media/seo_landing_files/f=
inding-area-of-trapezoid-with-sides-examples-1629184341.png" style=3D"width=
: 300px;"></p>
<p>From the above figure,</p>
<p>x + x + 13 =3D 17</p>
<p>2x + 13 =3D 17</p>
<p>2x =3D 4</p>
<p>x =3D 2</p>
<p>Using Pythagoras theorem,</p>
<p>x<sup>2</sup> + h<sup>2</sup> =3D 8<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>2<sup>2</sup> + h<sup>2</sup> =3D 64</p>
<p>4 + h<sup>2</sup> =3D 64</p>
<p>h<sup>2</sup> =3D 60</p>
<p>h =3D =E2=88=9A60 =3D =E2=88=9A4 =C3=97 =E2=88=9A15 =3D 2=E2=88=9A15</p>
<p>The area of the given trapezoid is,</p>
<p>A =3D =C2=BD (a + b) h</p>
<p>A =3D =C2=BD (13 + 17) =C3=97 (2=E2=88=9A15) =3D 30=E2=88=9A15 =3D 116.1=
8 square units</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> The area of the given trapezoid =3D 116.18 squa=
re units.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li class=3D"cue-slide" id=3D"slide-24">
<div>
<p><strong>Example 3:</strong> Find the area of a trapezoid in which the ba=
ses are given as 7 units and 9 units and the height is given as 5 units.</p=
>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The area of a trapezoid =3D =C2=BD (a + b) h;=
 where a =3D 7, b =3D 9, h =3D 5.</p>
<p>Substituting these values in the formula, we get:</p>
<p>A =3D =C2=BD (a + b) h</p>
<p>A =3D =C2=BD (7 + 9) =C3=97 5</p>
<p>A =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 16 =C3=97 5 =3D 40 unit<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>Therefore, the area of the trapezoid is 40 square units.</p>
</div>
</li>
